## Core Game Systems

### 1. Village Placement & Relocation

#### Initial Placement (Onboarding)
- During onboarding, the player opens a **full world Mapbox map** and taps anywhere on Earth to place their village.
- This coordinate becomes `village_origin` — the anchor for their entire game world.
- Players can optionally use their real current location, but this is never required or encouraged.
- The game never asks for, stores, or infers the player's real-world home address. Village origin is purely a game coordinate.
- **Privacy by design**: Since every player freely chooses their village location, seeing someone's village on a map tells you NOTHING about where they actually live. A village in Paris could belong to someone in Texas. This is an intentional, foundational privacy feature — not a workaround.

#### Village Relocation (Move Camp)
Moving your village is a strategic decision with real cost. It's not casual — it should feel like a caravan packing up and migrating across the world.

**Relocation cost scales with distance:**
| Move Distance | Mile Cost | Resource Cost | Narrative |
|---|---|---|---|
| Under 10 mi (local move) | 5 miles | 10 Wood | "The village relocated to nearby fertile ground." |
| 10–100 mi (regional move) | 15 miles | 20 Wood + 10 Stone | "A short migration to new territory." |
| 100–500 mi (cross-region) | 30 miles | 40 Wood + 20 Stone + 20 Food | "The great caravan traveled for days across the land." |
| 500–2,000 mi (cross-country) | 50 miles | 60 Wood + 30 Stone + 30 Food | "An epic migration across vast distances." |
| 2,000+ mi (intercontinental) | 75 miles | 80 Wood + 40 Stone + 40 Food + 20 Medicine | "A legendary journey across oceans and continents." |

**What happens when you relocate:**
- New village origin is set to the tapped location
- All buildings are preserved (they "travel with you" — no rebuilding)
- Fog of war resets around the new location (you have to re-explore the new area)
- Previously explored tiles at the old location remain explored (you can zoom out and see your full exploration history)
- A Chronicle entry is auto-generated: "The village of Thornhaven undertook a great migration from the forests of England to the mountains of Colorado."
- A faction event is posted: "Thornhaven has relocated! [Username] moved their village to a new region."
- Any active outposts at the old location remain (they become distant waypoints)

**Why players would relocate:**
- **Be neighbors with friends**: move your village near a faction member so you can see each other on the map and share landmarks
- **Chase World Events**: monthly events may be tied to regions or biomes. Moving to the right area gives strategic advantages
- **Better landmarks**: some real-world areas have denser Mapbox POIs (cities vs. rural). Relocating to a landmark-rich area means more in-game content to discover
- **Fresh exploration**: if you've fully explored your current area (all fog of war revealed), relocating gives you a whole new world to uncover
- **Roleplay / storytelling**: your Chronicle tracks every migration, building a narrative of your village's journey across the world
- **Faction strategy**: factions may want to cluster their villages in one region for territory dominance during competitive events

**No artificial cooldown.** The mile and resource costs ARE the gating mechanism — you don't need a timer on top. If someone has 75 miles banked and wants to move across the world twice in one week, they earned it. The expense naturally prevents frivolous moves without punishing dedicated players.

**Faction Migration (Group Discount):**
When faction members relocate to the same general area (within 25 miles of each other), they receive escalating discounts. This rewards coordinated movement and makes faction-wide migrations feel like a caravan traveling together.

| Faction Members Who Already Moved to This Area | Discount for Next Mover |
|---|---|
| 1 member already there | 10% off miles + resources |
| 2–4 members already there | 20% off |
| 5–9 members already there | 30% off |
| 10+ members already there | 40% off (cap) |

How it works:
- When a player opens the relocation screen, the app checks if any faction members have villages within 25 miles of the target location
- If yes, the discount is auto-applied and shown: "3 faction members are nearby — Caravan Discount: 20% off!"
- The discount applies to BOTH mile cost and resource cost
- A faction event is posted: "Thornhaven joined the caravan! 4 faction members now in the Alpine region."
- This creates a natural pull: once 2-3 faction members move somewhere, the rest are incentivized to follow because it gets cheaper

**Strategic implications:**
- Factions can coordinate migrations toward World Events at reduced cost
- A faction leader can announce "we're moving to the Pacific Coast this month" and early movers pave the way for cheaper moves for everyone else
- Being a faction "pioneer" (first to move to a new region) has social value even though you pay full price — you're the one who made it cheaper for everyone
- Chronicle entry for faction migrations: "The [Faction Name] caravan arrived in [Region] — [X] villages now stand together."

**Scouting before moving:** Players can browse the full world map at any time to scout potential relocation spots. Unexplored areas show fog of war but the base Mapbox terrain is visible (you can see if a location has mountains, rivers, coastline, etc.). A "Preview" mode shows how many POI landmarks are nearby before committing to the move.

### 2. Character & Avatar System

Every player has a personal character — their representative in the game world. The avatar appears in the village scene, on the world map, in the faction feed, and on their profile.

#### Art Style
Clean illustrated, fantasy-themed. Think Clash Royale meets Duolingo — expressive characters that read well at small sizes on mobile screens. Slightly medieval aesthetic to match the village theme.

#### Technical Implementation
Avatars are built from **composable SVG layers** rendered on a base template. This is production-efficient and allows infinite combinations without creating individual assets for every permutation.

#### Phase 1 Customization (Start Simple)
During onboarding (after naming village, before placing it), the player builds their character:

| Layer | Options (Phase 1) |
|---|---|
| Skin tone | 6 tones |
| Hair style | 8 styles (4 short, 4 long) |
| Hair color | 8 colors |
| Face shape | 4 shapes |
| Eyes | 6 styles |
| Outfit | 4 starter outfits (villager, scout, farmer, healer) |

All options are free. No paid customization in Phase 1.

#### Phase 2+ Expansion
- More hairstyles, facial hair, accessories (hats, cloaks, armor)
- **Movement-earned outfits**: unlock new gear at milestone achievements (100-mile cloak, 365-day streak crown)
- **Building-specific outfits**: building a Watchtower to Lv 3 unlocks a Guard Captain outfit
- **World Event exclusive cosmetics**: limited-time character items earned during events
- Realm Pass subscribers get access to a "Premium Wardrobe" with additional cosmetic options

#### Where the Avatar Appears
- **Village scene**: standing in the village square, animated idle pose
- **World map**: your map marker IS your avatar (small circular portrait)
- **Faction feed**: avatar portrait next to each RPG-narrated event
- **Faction member list**: avatar portraits with username and role
- **Profile**: large avatar display with achievement badges
- **Friend Challenges**: side-by-side avatar comparison during 1v1 duels
- **Leaderboard**: avatar portraits next to rankings

#### Avatar Data
Stored as a JSON object of selected layer IDs — lightweight, no image storage needed. The client renders the composite on-device from the layer assets bundled with the app.

### 3. Mile Banking & Allocation System
This is the core loop that separates FitRealm from other fitness games. **Movement is currency. Miles buy everything.**

#### Resource Economy Hierarchy
All resources in FitRealm flow from one source: physical movement converted into miles. The economy has three tiers:

| Tier | Source | % of Resources | Role |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Primary** | Mile allocations (player choice) | ~80% | The core loop. You move, you choose where those miles go. This IS the game. |
| **Secondary** | Building passive generation | ~15% | Safety net. Buys time on busy days. Never enough to sustain a village alone. |
| **Tertiary** | Streak bonuses, Rallies, quest rewards, events | ~5% | Small perks that reward engagement. Flavor, not sustenance. |

This hierarchy is non-negotiable. If any tuning change makes Secondary or Tertiary sources large enough to sustain a village without movement, that is a bug — rebalance immediately.

**Step 1 — Earn miles**: Any physical movement (outdoor GPS, treadmill, HealthKit sync). Miles are added to a **Mile Bank**.

**Step 2 — Choose your investment**: After logging activity, or any time from the home screen, the player opens the **Allocate screen** and decides how to spend banked miles. This is where strategy lives — do you feed your village now or invest in a building that reduces future decay?

| Allocation | Miles Cost | Effect | Narrative Flavor |
|---|---|---|---|
| Hunt for Food | 0.5 miles | +20 Food | "Your hunters ventured into the wild and returned with game." |
| Gather Medicine | 0.5 miles | +20 Medicine | "Your healers foraged the forest for herbs and remedies." |
| Chop Wood | 0.5 miles | +20 Wood | "Your workers felled timber from the nearby woods." |
| Quarry Stone | 1.0 mile | +10 Stone | "Your miners broke stone from the eastern cliffs." |
| Scout Region | 1.0 mile | Reveal fog-of-war tiles on map | "Your scouts mapped uncharted territory beyond the borders." |
| Explore New Land | 1.0 mile | Unlock a new territory tile | "Explorers discovered new land ripe for expansion." |
| Defend Village | 2.0 miles | Prevent next decay tick (one-time shield) | "The militia fortified the walls — the village is safe for now." |
| Contribute to Faction | Any amount | Donate miles to faction weekly quest pool | "You sent supplies to your allies across the realm." |
| Establish Outpost | 5.0 miles | Place an outpost at any explored location | "A new outpost was erected on the frontier." |
| Move Camp | 5–75 miles (scales with distance) | Relocate village to a new coordinate (see Village Relocation section for full cost table) | "The village packed up and began a great migration." |

Every allocation is a conscious decision: *"I walked 2 miles today. My Food is low but I'm saving for a Watchtower that needs 20 Wood. Do I hunt or chop?"* This decision-making IS the game. Without it, the app is just a step counter.

- Unspent miles sit in the bank indefinitely — no expiry in Phase 1.
- This gives players flexibility: treadmill runners accumulate miles and spend them strategically, same as outdoor runners.

#### Miles Economy at a Glance
Miles flow into and out of the player's bank like a real economy:

**Miles In:**
- Outdoor movement (GPS tracked)
- Indoor movement (manual entry or HealthKit/Health Connect sync)
- Movement type multipliers (running 1.25x, hiking 1.5x, walking 1.0x)

**Miles Out (player chooses):**
- Resource gathering: Food, Medicine, Wood, Stone (0.5–1.0 mi each)
- Map exploration: Scout, Explore (1.0 mi each)
- Defense: Defend Village (2.0 mi)
- Building construction: 3–20 miles per building depending on type and tier
- Building upgrades: increasing mile costs per tier
- Village relocation: Move Camp (5–75 mi, scales with distance)
- Outpost placement: Establish Outpost (5.0 mi)
- Faction support: Contribute to Faction (any amount)

The player is always asking: *"What does my village need most right now, and can I afford it?"* — this is what makes FitRealm a game, not a tracker.

### 4. Village Survival Loop
Each village has 4 resource meters (0–100):
- **Food** — replenished by Hunt allocations (any movement counts — a walk to the store feeds your village)
- **Medicine** — replenished by Gather allocations
- **Wood** — replenished by Chop allocations
- **Morale** — replenished by any allocation + faction activity + movement streaks
- **Stone** — earned via Quarry allocation, Lumber Mill Lv 2+, and some quests. Used exclusively for building construction/upgrades. Does not decay.

**Decay rules:**
- **No decay for the first 24 hours** after a player creates their village (grace period)
- After 24 hours: base decay of -8 points per 12 hours per resource (server-side cron via Vercel Cron)
  - Watchtower reduces this: Lv 1 = -10%, Lv 2 = -15%, Lv 3 = -20%
  - Farm/Herbalist/Lumber Mill passively add resources each tick, offsetting decay
- Resource hits 0: village shows visible damage in the UI
- All resources at 0 for 48 hours: village enters **Ruined** state

  **What "Ruined" looks and feels like:**
  The village scene shifts to a somber but NOT depressing visual — buildings are weathered, gardens are overgrown (not dead), villagers are sitting around a dim campfire. The tone is "sleeping kingdom waiting for its leader," not "punishment." Background music shifts to a quiet, hopeful melody.

  A banner across the screen reads: "Your village awaits your return."

  **Recovery options:**
  - Spend 5 banked miles → instant full recovery (all resources set to 50/100)
  - Complete the "Return of the Wanderer" comeback quest chain (3 quests over 3 days) → full recovery + bonus rewards
  - Realm Pass holders recover with resources at 60/100 instead of 50/100

  **What is NOT lost during Ruined state:**
  - Buildings remain at their current levels (you never lose construction progress)
  - Streak resets, but streak visual milestones on buildings are preserved
  - Achievement badges are permanent
  - Chronicle entries are permanent
  - Faction membership is maintained
  - All banked miles remain
  - Gems remain

  **Design intent:** Ruined state should feel like a dramatic story beat ("the kingdom fell into slumber"), not a punishment. The recovery should feel heroic ("the wanderer returned and rebuilt"). Players who hit Ruined and come back should feel MORE invested, not less.
- Completing any allocation resets a "last active" timestamp that slows decay slightly for active players

### 5. Activity Logging (Outdoor + Treadmill)
**Outdoor GPS runs:**
- In-app movement tracker with live Mapbox map, distance, pace, time
- Route stored as GeoJSON in Supabase Storage
- Kalman filter on GPS points to reduce noise
- Minimum GPS accuracy threshold: reject points with >20m accuracy

**Treadmill / Indoor runs (manual entry):**
- Log screen: enter distance + duration manually
- Optional: sync from Apple HealthKit (iOS) or Google Health Connect (Android)
  - If a workout is synced from Health, the app detects it and prompts "We found a 2.3-mile treadmill run — add to your mile bank?"
- Manual entries are flagged as `source: 'manual'` in the DB for potential anti-cheat review later

**Anti-cheat note (Phase 2):** For Phase 1, trust all inputs. In Phase 2, add rate limiting on manual entries (max X miles/day from manual) and anomaly detection on GPS routes.

### 6. Real-World Map Layer (Mapbox)
- Mapbox is the base layer with a **custom fantasy art style** applied (muted terrain colors, hidden road clutter, illustrated biome textures — forests, mountains, rivers — so it reads as a fantasy kingdom over real geography)
- Players feel grounded in their real city/country but the map looks like a medieval RPG world
- Village origin is the center of the player's game world
- **Fog of war**: ~1-mile hex tiles surrounding the village origin start hidden; unlocked by Scout allocations
- **Exploration reveal animation**: when Scout miles are allocated, fog-of-war hex tiles dissolve with a golden shimmer particle effect. The camera pans slightly outward from the village toward the newly revealed area. A toast notification appears: "Your scouts mapped the Western Marshlands!" If a landmark is revealed in the new tiles, it pops in with a bounce animation and a discovery notification: "A Trading Post was discovered!" This moment should feel like scratching a scratch-off ticket — satisfying and rewarding.
- **Landmark discovery**: each revealed tile is checked for Mapbox POIs. If a POI exists, it becomes a named in-game landmark with a unique icon. Discovering landmarks earns +5 Gems and a Chronicle entry.
- Mapbox POIs near the village origin become in-game landmarks:
  - `park` / `nature_reserve` → Forest
  - `hospital` / `pharmacy` → Healer's Hut
  - `marketplace` / `shop` → Trading Post
  - `river` / `lake` → River Crossing
  - `mountain` / `peak` → Mountain Pass
- Only user/village/faction markers update in real-time (via Supabase Realtime) — the base map is static tiles, not a live feed

#### Living World System (Tile Content Refresh)
Exploration should never feel "finished." The map is a living world where the geography is permanent but what's happening in it changes regularly.

**Two layers of map content:**

**Permanent Layer (never resets):**
- Fog of war: once a hex tile is revealed, it stays revealed forever
- Landmark POIs: Trading Posts, Forests, Healer's Huts, etc. — these are tied to real Mapbox POIs and remain fixed
- Your exploration history is permanent and visible on the map (you can zoom out and see every tile you've ever uncovered, across all relocations)

**Dynamic Layer (refreshes weekly, every Monday at midnight UTC):**
- **Resource caches**: random spawns in explored tiles — small icons showing gatherable resources. Tapping one triggers a mini-quest: "A berry bush was found in the eastern woods — gather it? (0.25 mi → +8 Food)"
- **Encounter spawns**: temporary threats or NPCs that appear in explored tiles. "A bandit camp appeared near the river crossing" — triggers a random quest with a time limit
- **Seasonal flora/fauna**: visual variety in explored tiles changes with real-world seasons (spring = flowers, winter = snow, fall = orange leaves). Purely cosmetic but keeps the map feeling alive
- **Rare spawns**: low-probability special discoveries in explored tiles (ancient ruins, hidden caves, mysterious traders). These give bonus Gems or exclusive cosmetic rewards. Rarity keeps players checking their map regularly.

**How the refresh works (server-side):**
- Vercel Cron job runs every Monday at midnight UTC: `/api/cron/refresh-tile-content`
- For each active player, the system generates new dynamic content across their explored tiles
- Content density: ~1 resource cache per 3 explored tiles, ~1 encounter per 5 tiles, ~1 rare spawn per 20 tiles
- Players are notified: "The world has shifted — new discoveries await in your explored lands! 🗺️"
- Dynamic content expires after 7 days (replaced by next week's refresh)
- Unexplored tiles have no dynamic content — you must Scout first to unlock content spawns

**Why this works:**
- Players who've explored their entire area still have weekly reasons to check the map and do mini-quests
- The map feels alive and unpredictable without erasing the player's exploration progress
- "What spawned this week?" becomes a Monday morning ritual — a natural engagement hook
- Rare spawns create variable reward excitement (the slot machine effect, but earned through exploration)
- Faction members can share tips: "There's a rare trader in the northern tiles this week!" — driving social engagement

### 7. Expedition System (Road Trips & Travel)
Travel in the real world triggers rare, high-reward **Expedition events** in the game. This rewards players who travel without letting it replace daily fitness.

**How it works:**
- The app passively detects vehicle-speed movement (>25 mph sustained for >10 minutes) via GPS during an active session or via HealthKit/Google Health travel detection
- On arrival, the app prompts: "You traveled X miles — an Expedition occurred!"
- The player names the expedition and it appears on their map as a journey arc

**What expeditions reward (exploration only — never Food/Medicine/Wood):**
| Travel Distance | Expedition Reward |
|---|---|
| 25–99 miles | Reveal a large fog-of-war region on the map |
| 100–299 miles | Discover a rare landmark (dungeon, ancient ruins, hidden market) |
| 300–999 miles | Unlock a distant region + place a temporary **Outpost** at the destination |
| 1,000+ miles | Discover a **Legendary Site** — generates bonus quests for 7 days |

**Outposts:**
- A secondary anchor point on the map (e.g. you drove to another city)
- Generates 1 bonus quest per day for 3 days after the trip
- Can be upgraded to a permanent **Waypoint** by completing those quests

**Critical design rule — expeditions never replace fitness:**
- Expedition rewards are exploration/map rewards only
- Food, Medicine, Wood, and Morale can ONLY be replenished by physical activity (running, walking)
- This keeps the fitness loop as the non-negotiable heartbeat of the game
- A player who only road trips will have a richly explored map but a decaying village

**Faction expeditions:**
- If a faction member travels to another faction member's city, it triggers a "Faction Envoy" event
- Rewards both players with bonus morale and a shared faction quest

### 8. Factions & Multiplayer
- Players can form or join a **Faction** (up to 20 members, Phase 1)
- Factions are not geographically restricted — friends anywhere can faction together
- Faction members can see each other on a shared map view (opt-in, shows village origins + avatar portraits)
- **Faction quests**: weekly collective mile goals (e.g. "Log 75 miles total this week → unlock Faction Stronghold")
- Members contribute miles from their bank to faction quests
- Activity feed powered by **Supabase Realtime**: events insert into `faction_events` table, all members subscribed

#### Faction Governance
Factions need clear rules to prevent drama and handle edge cases:

**Roles:**
| Role | Permissions |
|---|---|
| **Leader** | Kick members, promote to Co-Leader, set faction name/description, create custom faction quests (Realm Pass), disband faction |
| **Co-Leader** | Kick members (except Leader/Co-Leaders), accept join requests |
| **Member** | Participate in quests, Rally, contribute miles, view feed |

**Leader inactivity:**
- If the Leader has not logged any activity for 14 consecutive days, a notification is sent: "Your faction leader has been inactive. Leadership may transfer soon."
- After 21 days of Leader inactivity: leadership automatically transfers to the most active Co-Leader (by total miles in the last 30 days). If no Co-Leaders exist, it transfers to the most active Member.
- A faction event is posted: "Leadership of [Faction Name] has passed to [New Leader]."

**Joining & leaving:**
- Factions can be set to **Open** (anyone joins instantly) or **Request** (Leader/Co-Leader must approve)
- A player can leave a faction at any time. Contributed miles to faction quests are NOT refunded.
- A player can only be in 1 faction at a time
- After leaving or being kicked, the player must wait 24 hours before joining another faction (prevents hopping for rewards)

**Kicking:**
- Leader/Co-Leader can kick a member. Kicked player receives a notification but no reason is required.
- Kicked players keep all personal progress (village, buildings, streaks, achievements, gems)
- A kicked player cannot rejoin the same faction for 7 days

**Disbanding:**
- Only the Leader can disband a faction. Requires confirmation ("This will remove all members. Are you sure?")
- All members keep personal progress. Faction quest progress is lost.
- A 48-hour warning is sent to all members before disbanding takes effect

### 9. Building System

Buildings make your village feel personal and give long-term players a strategic investment layer. Every building is earned through movement — there is no way to buy buildings with real money or gems.

#### Design Philosophy
- Buildings create **long-term goals** that keep players engaged beyond daily survival
- Each building either reduces decay pressure, boosts earnings, or unlocks a mechanic
- Building costs use a **mix of resources + miles** — every building requires miles to construct, reinforcing that movement is the foundation of everything. The trade-off: spend miles on immediate survival (food, medicine) or invest in infrastructure that reduces future pressure? This is the core strategic tension of FitRealm
- Buildings visually appear in the village scene at **pre-set slots** (6 zones in the village view), not free-placement grid
- Each building has **3 upgrade tiers** with increasing costs and compounding benefits
- Visual progression per tier: Level 1 = basic wooden structure, Level 2 = stone walls + details, Level 3 = impressive fortified version

#### Village Layout (Pre-Set Slots)
The village scene has 6 designated building zones arranged around a central village square:

```
         [Watchtower]
              |
[Lumber Mill] ---- [Farm]
              |
        [Village Square]
         (always present)
              |
  [Herbalist] ---- [Tavern]
              |
         [Storehouse]
```

- The Village Square is always visible (it's the "heart" — shows villagers, streak visuals, celebrations)
- Each slot starts empty with a "Build" prompt
- Players choose which building to construct first — this is a strategic decision
- All 6 slots are available from the start but building costs increase, so players naturally build 1-2 first and expand over time

#### Building Definitions

**🌾 Farm**
Purpose: Passive Food generation — reduces the pressure to constantly allocate miles to hunting.

| Level | Build Cost | Effect | Visual |
|---|---|---|---|
| Lv 1 | 3 miles + 20 Wood | +1 Food per decay tick (every 6 hours) | Small garden plot with crops |
| Lv 2 | 6 miles + 40 Wood + 15 Stone | +2 Food per decay tick | Fenced farm with rows of crops |
| Lv 3 | 12 miles + 80 Wood + 30 Stone | +3 Food per decay tick + occasionally generates a bonus random quest related to harvesting | Large farm with barn, animated workers |

**💊 Herbalist Hut**
Purpose: Passive Medicine generation.

| Level | Build Cost | Effect | Visual |
|---|---|---|---|
| Lv 1 | 3 miles + 20 Wood | +1 Medicine per decay tick | Small hut with herb garden |
| Lv 2 | 6 miles + 40 Wood + 15 Stone | +2 Medicine per decay tick | Expanded hut with greenhouse |
| Lv 3 | 12 miles + 80 Wood + 30 Stone | +3 Medicine per decay tick + Rest Days restore +3 to all resources | Stone apothecary with glowing herbs |

**🪓 Lumber Mill**
Purpose: Passive Wood generation + produces Stone (the new building material).

| Level | Build Cost | Effect | Visual |
|---|---|---|---|
| Lv 1 | 5 miles + 30 Food | +1 Wood per decay tick | Log pile with basic saw |
| Lv 2 | 8 miles + 50 Food + 15 Stone | +2 Wood per decay tick + generates 2 Stone per decay tick | Water-powered sawmill |
| Lv 3 | 15 miles + 80 Food + 40 Stone | +3 Wood per decay tick + generates 3 Stone per decay tick + 5% mile multiplier on all movement | Full lumber mill with animated wheel |

**🏰 Watchtower**
Purpose: Defensive — slows resource decay across the board.

| Level | Build Cost | Effect | Visual |
|---|---|---|---|
| Lv 1 | 5 miles + 20 Wood + 10 Stone | Decay rate reduced by 10% for all resources | Short wooden lookout tower |
| Lv 2 | 10 miles + 40 Wood + 30 Stone | Decay rate reduced by 15% + random quest events give +2 bonus to rewards | Tall stone watchtower with flag |
| Lv 3 | 20 miles + 80 Wood + 60 Stone | Decay rate reduced by 20% + doubles the faction-wide random quest frequency + unlocks "Early Warning" (push notification 2 hours before any resource hits 0) | Fortified tower with beacon fire |

**🍺 Tavern**
Purpose: Morale hub + social feature booster.

| Level | Build Cost | Effect | Visual |
|---|---|---|---|
| Lv 1 | 4 miles + 25 Wood | +2 Morale per decay tick + Rallies received give +3 Morale instead of +2 | Small wooden tavern |
| Lv 2 | 8 miles + 50 Wood + 20 Stone | +3 Morale per decay tick + unlock "Tavern Tales" (see fun stats: faction's total miles this week, most active member, biggest single session) | Two-story tavern with sign |
| Lv 3 | 15 miles + 80 Wood + 50 Stone | +4 Morale per decay tick + Rallies received give +5 Morale + Friend Challenge winners get double gem rewards | Grand tavern with outdoor seating, music notes animated |

**📦 Storehouse**
Purpose: Increases resource caps and mile bank capacity — lets players stockpile for big investments.

| Level | Build Cost | Effect | Visual |
|---|---|---|---|
| Lv 1 | 4 miles + 25 Wood | Resource caps increase from 100 → 125 + Mile bank cap: unlimited (no change, but storehouse tracks total banked) | Small shed with crates |
| Lv 2 | 8 miles + 50 Wood + 20 Stone | Resource caps increase to 150 + allocation costs reduced by 10% (0.5 mi hunt → 0.45 mi) | Stone warehouse with shelves |
| Lv 3 | 15 miles + 80 Wood + 50 Stone | Resource caps increase to 200 + allocation costs reduced by 20% + "Surplus" mechanic: when any resource is above 150, excess slowly converts to Gems (1 Gem per 10 surplus per day) | Grand storehouse with gold accents, overflowing goods |

#### Stone: The Building Material

Stone is a new resource used exclusively for building construction and upgrades (Levels 2+). It cannot be "allocated" like Food/Medicine/Wood — it must be produced.

**How to earn Stone:**
- **Lumber Mill Level 2+**: Passively generates Stone every decay tick
- **Quarry allocation**: New allocation option — spend 1.0 mile to gain +10 Stone
- **Expedition rewards**: Some expeditions grant Stone as a bonus
- **Random quest rewards**: Some quests award Stone alongside other resources

Stone is stored separately from the 4 main resources and has no cap. It does not decay.

#### New Allocation Option

Add to the Allocate Miles screen:

| Allocation | Miles Cost | Effect |
|---|---|---|
| Quarry Stone | 1.0 mile | +10 Stone |

#### Building Construction Flow

1. Player taps an empty building slot in the village view
2. A panel shows the 6 available buildings with costs and effects
3. Player selects a building → confirmation screen shows cost breakdown
4. If player has enough resources + miles → "Build" button is active
5. On confirm: resources deducted, miles deducted, building appears in the village with a construction animation
6. Building is immediately functional (no build timers — this is NOT CoC. You earned it through movement, it's yours now.)
7. Chronicle entry auto-generated: "A Farm was erected on the eastern fields of Thornhaven."

#### Building Upgrade Flow

1. Player taps an existing building
2. Panel shows current level, current effects, and next level preview
3. Cost for next level displayed
4. If player has enough resources + miles → "Upgrade" button
5. On confirm: upgrade animation, building visuals change, effects immediately active
6. Chronicle entry: "The Farm was expanded — stone walls now protect the harvest."

#### Critical Balance Rule: Buildings NEVER Replace Movement

Buildings are a safety net, not an autopilot. At maximum level (all 6 buildings at Lv 3 + Watchtower), the math works out to:

- Base decay: -8 per resource per tick
- Watchtower Lv 3: reduces decay by 20% → effective decay = -6.4 per tick
- Farm Lv 3: +3 Food per tick → net Food loss = -3.4 per tick
- Herbalist Lv 3: +3 Medicine per tick → net Medicine loss = -3.4 per tick
- Lumber Mill Lv 3: +3 Wood per tick → net Wood loss = -3.4 per tick
- Tavern Lv 3: +4 Morale per tick → net Morale loss = -2.4 per tick

**Even a fully maxed village still loses resources every tick.** Buildings slow the bleed from -8/tick to roughly -3/tick, giving players more forgiveness for busy days — but a player who stops moving entirely will still watch their village decay and eventually enter Ruined state. This is non-negotiable.

The design intent: buildings buy you TIME, not freedom. A player with no buildings misses one day and is in trouble. A player with maxed buildings can miss 2-3 days before things get critical. But both players still need to move to thrive.

If future balancing makes buildings too strong, always nerf building output — never increase decay rates. The player should never feel punished; they should feel like buildings help but aren't enough alone.

#### Strategic Depth

The building costs are designed so that:
- **First building** (any Lv 1): achievable in the first 1-2 weeks of play
- **Second building**: another week of consistent movement
- **First Lv 2 upgrade**: requires Lumber Mill Lv 2 for Stone production, so players must plan
- **All 6 at Lv 1**: roughly 1 month of consistent daily movement
- **All 6 at Lv 3**: a long-term goal (2-3 months) — this is the "endgame" for dedicated players

The Lumber Mill is the strategic keystone: it produces both Wood AND Stone, so players who build it early unlock faster access to everything else. But it costs Food instead of Wood, creating a trade-off: spend Food now to invest in infrastructure, or keep Food high for survival safety.

